{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492400"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:27:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:27:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1049"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1049"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.18,0.04,0.1,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1049"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"22069"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1049"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1049"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"10940"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"583"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2607"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2782"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42209"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"22069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/22069"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man returns to his general practitioner (GP) for review of blood pressure management. In recent times, his blood pressure has been difficult to control, despite the use of multiple anti-hypertensive agents. He currently takes a combined tablet of perindopril arginine-amlodipine 10mg/10mg PO mane, as well as hydrochlorothiazide 25mg PO mane. He has no significant medical conditions, aside from hypertension diagnosed two years ago. He does not snore at night. At the time of diagnosis, he gave up smoking and alcohol on the advice of his GP. He avoids adding any salt to his food and performs at least two hours of moderate-intensity exercise each week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His vital signs are all normal, except for blood pressure at 166/94mmHg. His BMI is currently 24 (weight 80kg, height 183cm). Cardiorespiratory examination and abdominal exam are unremarkable. His upper/lower limb power and reflexes are normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn the advice of a colleague, the GP orders a CT scan of the abdomen (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following abnormal laboratory findings is the man most likely to have?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hyperkalaemia","Raised serum cortisol","Hyponatraemia","Raised serum creatinine","Raised serum aldosterone-renin ratio"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer to this question is \u003Cstrong\u003Eraised serum aldosterone-renin ratio.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a history of hypertension that is refractory to medical therapy, despite taking three anti-hypertensive medications. His physical examination is normal and he is not overweight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis CT scan demonstrates a \u003Cstrong\u003Eright sided adrenal adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E. Such lesions are common and found in perhaps 5% of the adult population. Whilst the majority are non-functioning and benign, some adenomas can produce excessive aldosterone, known as primary hyperaldosteronism (Conn syndrome), a well-known cause of secondary hypertension. Classically, patients with this condition will present with a history of hypertension that is not responsive to medical therapy or lifestyle changes. Aldosterone secretion by the adrenal cortex occurs independent of the homeostatic RAAS mechanism, leading to increased sodium and water retention by the kidneys. The result is higher blood pressures and an increased serum aldosterone-renin ratio. Definitive treatment of primary hyperaldosteronism caused by an adrenal adenoma, is surgical resection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperkalaemia\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyponatraemia\u003C/strong\u003E are both incorrect answer options. In primary hyperaldosteronism syndrome, excessive aldosterone secretion by the adrenal gland leads to increased sodium reabsorption by the kidneys, as well as increased urinary potassium losses. Hypokalaemia is a common laboratory abnormality in primary hyperaldosteronism and depending on the patient\u0027s volume status, hypernatraemia can be observed too.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERaised serum cortisol\u003C/strong\u003E is an incorrect option. There is no evidence to suggest Cushing\u0027s syndrome and thus, serum cortisol should be normal. Whilst Cushing\u0027s syndrome is a cause of secondary hypertension, it is associated with a constellation of symptoms and signs, in addition to the hypertension. Some of these include weight gain, fatigue, mood swings, poor sleep, acne, skin thinning, easy bruising, fat redistribution, cutaneous striae and proximal myopathy. This man exhibits none of these features and thus, this answer option is not correct.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERaised serum creatinine\u003C/strong\u003E is an incorrect option. Adrenal adenomas are not generally associated with renal dysfunction and thus, one would expect the serum creatinine to be normal. In older patients with risk factors (e.g. longstanding diabetes mellitus and primary hypertension), renal impairment is an important cause of secondary hypertension. This man exhibits no risk factors for chronic kidney disease (hypertension aside!), and given the fact he is only 56 years old, renal dysfunction is quite unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Whilst the majority of adrenal adenomas are non-functioning and benign, some can produce excessive aldosterone, known as primary hyperaldosteronism (Conn syndrome), a well-known cause of secondary hypertension."],"references":["Lee FT, Elaraj D. Evaluation and management of primary hyperaldosteronism. The Surgical Clinics of North America. 2019 Aug;99(4):731\u201345"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"10940"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1049"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14579"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14579"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/54129229-f5ed-48eb-a556-b35db38cc5bf.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/54129229-f5ed-48eb-a556-b35db38cc5bf.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":467}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"10940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/10940"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-03-31T13:48:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-03-31T13:48:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1049"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"22069"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":